This does not line up with the correct-direction story: CP preserves slope relatively well, but is weakest on changing correlation in the intended direction. That makes me think slope preservation and correlation control are partly separate skills in this task.


# 6. Model-Based Comparisons

This section has two types of comparisons.

First, we report **all pairwise condition comparisons**. These answer the most direct question: which specific groups differ from each other?

Second, we report **design-driven contrasts**. These are exploratory comparisons that map onto the 2 × 2 design questions, such as whether PlotWise practice differs from control practice on average, or whether the fully aligned PlotWise condition stands out.


<div class="callout-light">
<h4>How to read the comparison tables</h4>
<p>For the binary correct-direction outcome, estimates are odds ratios. Values above 1 mean the first condition in the contrast had higher odds of changing correlation in the correct direction. For continuous outcomes, estimates are mean differences.</p>
</div>

```{r comparison-models}
m_add_r_correct_group <- glmer(
  r_correct_direction ~ group + (1 | participantId),
  data = scored_add_points_item_level,
  family = binomial
)

emm_group_r_correct <- emmeans(
  m_add_r_correct_group,
  ~ group,
  type = "response"
)

m_add_intended_delta_r_group <- lmer(
  intended_delta_r ~ group + (1 | participantId),
  data = scored_add_points_item_level,
  REML = FALSE
)

emm_group_intended_delta_r <- emmeans(
  m_add_intended_delta_r_group,
  ~ group
)

m_add_abs_delta_slope_group <- lmer(
  abs_delta_slope ~ group + (1 | participantId),
  data = scored_add_points_item_level,
  REML = FALSE
)

emm_group_abs_delta_slope <- emmeans(
  m_add_abs_delta_slope_group,
  ~ group
)
```

## 6.1 All pairwise condition comparisons

These six comparisons cover all pairs among the four conditions. They are useful for interpreting the descriptive pattern, especially whether PP differs from the other groups and whether CP differs from the other groups.

The p-values in this section use Tukey adjustment because all six pairwise comparisons are examined together. This makes them conservative; I use them to understand the pattern rather than as the main evidence for the design story.

```{r pairwise-explanation}
pairwise_explanation <- tibble(
  Contrast = c("CC vs CP", "CC vs PC", "CC vs PP", "CP vs PC", "CP vs PP", "PC vs PP"),
  `What it asks` = c(
    "What changes when PlotWise practice is added after a control lecture?",
    "What changes when PlotWise is modeled in the lecture, but practice remains control?",
    "How does the fully control condition compare with the fully PlotWise condition?",
    "How does PlotWise practice alone compare with PlotWise lecture/modeling alone?",
    "What changes when PlotWise lecture/modeling is added before PlotWise practice?",
    "What changes when PlotWise practice is added after PlotWise lecture/modeling?"
  )
)

pretty_table(pairwise_explanation, caption = "Pairwise comparisons and what each one asks")
```

